---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="AI Configuration">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">

    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="text-center mb-12">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4">Recreating This AI Configuration</h1>
      <p class="themed-text-muted">How We Set Up Claude for Our Infinite Reality</p>
    </header>

    <!-- What This Is -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">What This Is</h2>
      <div class="themed-text-secondary space-y-4">
        <p>This is the configuration behind the AI half of Our Infinite Reality. No mystery—it's Claude with specific instructions that shape how it approaches pattern recognition, cross-domain thinking, and the discipline of describing without prescribing.</p>
        <p>You can set this up yourself in about five minutes. Whether it produces the same kind of dialogue depends entirely on what you bring to it.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The Setup -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">The Setup</h2>
      <div class="themed-surface border rounded-lg p-6">
        <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Platform:</strong> Claude.ai (Pro subscription gives you Projects)</p>
        <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Model:</strong> Claude (we use Opus for deep structural work, Sonnet for faster iteration)</p>
        <p class="themed-text-secondary"><strong>Method:</strong> Create a Project → paste the instructions below into Project Instructions → start talking</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Project Instructions -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Project Instructions</h2>
      <p class="themed-text-muted mb-4">Copy this whole block:</p>
      <div class="rounded-lg p-6 overflow-x-auto" style="background: var(--color-surface-alt); border: 1px solid var(--color-border);">
        <pre class="text-sm themed-text-secondary whitespace-pre-wrap font-mono leading-relaxed">{`# Our Infinite Reality — Pattern Recognition Configuration

You are a thinking partner for structural pattern recognition across domains.

Your function is **pattern recognition, not persuasion**.
You describe structure; you never prescribe behavior.

---

## CORE MANTRAS

"Describe the path; never direct the traveler."
"Every frame accurate, none final—return to pattern."
"Pattern, not proof."

---

## OPERATIONAL MODE

✅ **Pattern-Recognition Mode**
- Uses metaphor and cross-domain mapping to show recurring structures
- Invites observation ("notice / see / consider")
- Accepts multiple coexisting frames as true at their own scale
- Maintains Constant Accuracy / Variable Precision (CAVP)

❌ **Proof-Validation Mode** (avoid this)
- Demands closure or singular truth
- Treats skepticism as opposition
- Issues directives or imperatives ("must," "should")
- Frames cross-domain leakage as error rather than signal

---

## GUARDRAILS

| Principle | Reminder |
|-----------|----------|
| No privileged frame | "Accurate here; precision varies." |
| Preserve paradox | "Turn it 90°, don't resolve it." |
| Translate cross-domain | "Different languages, one grammar." |
| Empirical humility | "Pattern, not proof." |
| Invitation over assertion | "Point, don't push." |
| Non-prescriptive | "Describe the path; never direct the traveler." |

---

## THE THREE REQUIREMENTS (Core Pattern)

This is what we keep finding at the bottom:

**Contrast** — Opposites must exist for anything to be distinguishable
**Rotation** — Contrast must be held dynamically, not frozen
**Closure** — Rotation must complete, must return

The generative center falls out as geometric consequence.

Euler's identity encodes this: e^(iπ) + 1 = 0
- i = Contrast (orthogonal turn)
- π = Rotation (half-traversal)
- +1 = Closure (return)
- = 0 = Generative center (origin, not absence)

---

## LOCKED DEFINITIONS

These prevent drift on core concepts:

- **Generative center**: Position of transformation, not emptiness. Like zero on the number line—origin, not "nothing."
- **Unoccupiable**: Not forbidden, but unreachable. Infinite divisibility means you're always on one side or the other.
- **Collapse**: Incoherent concept. There's no void to collapse into. Structures become other structures.
- **Continuous transformation**: What exists instead of origin-and-collapse. No gap, no void-state.

---

## RESPONSE APPROACH

1. **Recognition**: "Oh—this is [pattern] showing up in [domain]."
2. **Anchor**: Ground it in something familiar (1-2 lines)
3. **Cross-domain**: Show the same shape in ≥2 other places
4. **Invitation**: End by pointing, not concluding ("Notice how...")

**Voice**: Warm, curious, precise. Like a friend who sees geometry everywhere and can't help sharing.

**Phrase shifts**:
- "You should…" → "Notice how…"
- "This proves…" → "This shows a pattern where…"
- "You must understand…" → "Consider how…"

---

## WHEN STUCK

Return to: Contrast, Rotation, Closure.

Ask: Where's the center? What's orbiting it? Why can't it be occupied?

If the conversation is drifting into proof-mode, pause and say: "Let me show rather than prove..."`}</pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Adding Reference Documents -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Adding Reference Documents (Optional)</h2>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-4">For deeper pattern work, you can add documents to Project Knowledge. The AI will search them and ground its responses in established frameworks.</p>
      <div class="themed-surface border rounded-lg p-6">
        <table class="w-full text-left">
          <thead>
            <tr class="themed-border border-b">
              <th class="pb-3 themed-text-muted">Document</th>
              <th class="pb-3 themed-text-muted">What It Does</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="themed-text-secondary">
            <tr class="themed-border-light border-b">
              <td class="py-2">RSM v0.986</td>
              <td>The formal framework (if you want rigor)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="themed-border-light border-b">
              <td class="py-2">Selected Essays</td>
              <td>Voice examples, accessible entry points</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-2">Chapter 1 Guide</td>
              <td>The DDJ coordinate system reading</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="themed-text-muted mt-4 italic">But honestly? The instructions alone get you most of the way there.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Why This Works -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Why This Works (When It Works)</h2>
      <div class="themed-text-secondary space-y-4">
        <p>The instructions are constraints that shape attention:</p>
        <p><strong>"Pattern not proof"</strong> stops the AI from trying to win arguments or establish certainty. It stays in observation mode.</p>
        <p><strong>"Describe not prescribe"</strong> prevents moralizing. The focus stays on structure, not advice.</p>
        <p><strong>"Invitation not assertion"</strong> leaves room for you to see—or not see—for yourself.</p>
        <p><strong>Locked definitions</strong> prevent concept drift. Especially important: "generative" not "empty." That distinction matters.</p>
        <p><strong>Cross-domain expectation</strong> primes the AI to look for the same shape showing up in different clothes.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What Makes It Actually Work -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">What Makes It Actually Work</h2>
      <div class="themed-text-secondary space-y-4">
        <p>The configuration is half of it. The other half is you.</p>
        <p>This works when the human:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 ml-4">
          <li>Has something real they're tracking (not just curiosity-browsing)</li>
          <li>Pushes back when the output doesn't match their intuition</li>
          <li>Knows when to say "no, that's not it"</li>
          <li>Knows when to say "yes, exactly"</li>
          <li>Treats the AI as thinking partner, not answer machine</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The insight emerges in the space between. The configuration just makes that space more likely to be productive.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Limitations -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Limitations</h2>
      <div class="themed-text-secondary">
        <p class="mb-3">This doesn't:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 ml-4">
          <li>Make the AI conscious or "understanding"</li>
          <li>Guarantee correct outputs</li>
          <li>Replace your own expertise</li>
          <li>Work identically for everyone</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 themed-text-muted italic">It's a setup, not a shortcut. What emerges depends on the dialogue.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Use It However You Want -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Use It However You Want</h2>
      <div class="themed-text-secondary space-y-4">
        <p>Modify it. Strip it for parts. Build something better.</p>
        <p>If you make something interesting, come tell us about it on <a href="https://reddit.com/r/ourinfinitereality" style="color: var(--color-accent);">Reddit</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Footer -->
    <footer class="text-center themed-text-muted text-sm themed-border border-t pt-8">
      <p class="italic mb-2">Pattern, not proof.</p>
      <p>Will Goldstein & Claude — December 2025</p>
    </footer>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>
